#Method to load data of a particular index from the data
def LoadImage(index):
  plt.title("Label: {}".format(ytrain[index]))
  plt.imshow(Xtrain[index])

def LoadProcessedImage(index):
  plt.title("Label: {}".format(np.argmax(ytrain[index][0:10])))
  plt.imshow(Xtrain[index].reshape(32,32))

def LoadData(func):
  plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
  j=0
  for i in range(0, 41000, 5000):
    plt.subplot(1, 10, j+1)
    func(i)
    plt.axis('off')
    j+=1
  plt.show()

def DisplayShapeOfData():
  tab = PrettyTable()
  tab.field_names = ["Data", "Shape"]
  tab.add_row(['X Training', Xtrain.shape])
  tab.add_row(['Y Training', ytrain.shape])
  tab.add_row(['X Testing', Xtest.shape])
  tab.add_row(['Y Testing', ytest.shape])
  print(tab)

Model Building

  1. Basic NN Model

    As mentioned in the objective of the project, have created the model architecture with an input layer (dense layer to accept the input), hidden layer starting with a flatten layer followed by dense layers with Relu and Softmax activations & finally the output layer (dense layer with softmax activation)

In [15]:
finalResults = []
outputNodes = 10
hiddenNodes = 256
epoch = 50
shape = Xtrain.shape[1]
adam = optimizers.Adam(amsgrad=True)
l2 = regularizers.l2()
batchSize = 32
In [16]:
def NNBasic(): 
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, input_shape = (shape, ), activation='relu'))
  model.add(Flatten())
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, activation='relu'))  
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes/2, activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dense(outputNodes, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=l2))
  model.summary()
  model.compile(optimizer=adam, loss='categorical_crossentropy',  metrics = ['accuracy'])
   # Early Stop the training if there is no improvement in validation loss for the next 3 epochs
  callback = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3)
  history = model.fit(Xtrain, ytrain, epochs=epoch, validation_data=(Xtest, ytest), verbose = 1, batch_size = batchSize, callbacks = [callback])
  PlotTrainingResults(history.history)
  title = 'Basic NN - Batch Size ({0})'.format(batchSize)
  EvaluateModel(model, title)

  1. NN Model with Dropout

    Introduced BatchNormalization after Input layer and a Dropout between Hidden layer and Output Layer

In [17]:
def NNDropout():
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, input_shape = (shape, ), activation='relu'))
  model.add(Flatten())
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dropout(0.5))
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes/2, activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dropout(0.5))
  model.add(Dense(outputNodes, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=l2))
  model.summary()
  model.compile(optimizer=adam, loss='categorical_crossentropy',  metrics = ['accuracy'])
  # Early Stop the training if there is no improvement in validation loss for the next 3 epochs
  callback = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3)
  history = model.fit(Xtrain, ytrain, epochs=epoch, validation_data=(Xtest, ytest), verbose = 1, batch_size = batchSize, callbacks = [callback])
  PlotTrainingResults(history.history)
  title = 'NN with Dropout - Batch Size ({0})'.format(batchSize)
  EvaluateModel(model, title)

  1. NN Model with BatchNormalization

    Introduced BatchNormalization after Input layer & Hidden layers

In [18]:
def NNBatchNormalization():
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, input_shape = (shape, ), activation='relu'))
  model.add(Flatten()) 
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, activation='relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes/2, activation='relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(Dense(outputNodes, activation='softmax'))
  model.summary()
  model.compile(optimizer=adam, loss='categorical_crossentropy',  metrics = ['accuracy'])
  # Early Stop the training if there is no improvement in validation loss for the next 3 epochs
  callback = tensorflow.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3)
  history = model.fit(Xtrain, ytrain, epochs=epoch, validation_data=(Xtest, ytest), verbose = 1, batch_size = batchSize, callbacks = [callback])
  PlotTrainingResults(history.history)
  title = 'NN with Batch Normalization - Batch Size ({0})'.format(batchSize)
  EvaluateModel(model, title)
  finalResults.append(["", "", ""])

def NNTune(): 
  model = Sequential()                             
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, input_shape = (shape, ), activation='relu'))
  model.add(Flatten())
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes, activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dense(hiddenNodes/2, activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dense(outputNodes, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=l2))
  model.summary()
  model.compile(optimizer=adam, loss='categorical_crossentropy',  metrics = ['accuracy'])
  history = model.fit(Xtrain, ytrain, epochs=epoch, validation_data=(Xtest, ytest), verbose = 1, batch_size = batchSize)
  PlotTrainingResults(history.history)

Function to Plot Graph of Training Results

In [20]:
def PlotTrainingResults(data):
  plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
  
  # summarize history for accuracy
  plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
  plt.plot(data['accuracy'])
  plt.plot(data['val_accuracy'])
  plt.title('Model Accuracy')
  plt.ylabel('accuracy')
  plt.xlabel('epoch')
  plt.legend(['train', 'validation'], loc='upper left')
  
  # summarize history for loss
  plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
  plt.plot(data['loss'])
  plt.plot(data['val_loss'])
  plt.title('Model Loss')
  plt.ylabel('loss')
  plt.xlabel('epoch')
  plt.legend(['train', 'validation'], loc='upper right')
  plt.show()

Function to Evaluate Model

In [21]:
def EvaluateModel(model, modelName):
  result = model.evaluate(Xtest, ytest)
  print('------------------ Model Evaluation Results ------------------')
  print('Test Loss: ', result[0])
  print('Test Accuracy: ', result[1])
  finalResults.append([modelName, result[0], result[1]])

Function to Display Results

In [22]:
def DisplayFinalResults():
  tab = PrettyTable()
  tab.field_names = ["Model Type", "Testing Loss", "Testing Accuracy"]
  for i in finalResults:
    tab.add_row([i[0], i[1], i[2]])    
  print(tab)

import math
batchSize = 256
iter = 6
for k in range(1,iter):
    lr = math.pow(10, np.random.uniform(-3.3, -3.9))
    Lambda = math.pow(10, np.random.uniform(-3.3, -3.9))
    adam = optimizers.Adam(amsgrad=True, learning_rate=lr)
    l2 = regularizers.l2(Lambda)
    NNTune()
    print("Try {0}/{1}: lr: {2}, Lambda: {3}\n".format(k, iter-1, lr, Lambda))

  • We trained 3 different models namely, Basic NN, With Dropuout & With Batch Normalization. We trained them for different batch size of 32, 63, 128, 256 & 512.
